2008/10/23 David Jackman &lt;david.jackman@...&gt;:
&gt; I haven&#39;t really thought this through (so ignore me if I&#39;m missing something
&gt; that should be obvious), but since JUnit now identifies test classes with
&gt; attributes, would there be an advantage to having two different types of
&gt; test classes (i.e. two different attributes): one for test classes that
&gt; behave as they do now and one for test classes that keep the same instance
&gt; for all tests?

I think that can already be implemented with a test runner.

E.g.

@RunWith(SharedInstance.class)
public class BananaTests {
    BananaTree tree = growBananaTreeForTenYears();

    @Test
    public void tastesDelicious()
        Banana b = tree.pickBanana();
        ...
    }
    ...
}


